### Code Splitting

Code splitting breaks your bundle into smaller chunks loaded on demand. React.lazy and Suspense are the primary tools for component-level splitting, while dynamic imports handle module-level splitting.

---

### Dynamic Import

```jsx
// Instead of static import:
// import { format } from './utils';

// Dynamic import (loaded when needed):
const formatModule = await import('./utils');
```

### Webpack and Vite Configuration

Both Vite and webpack automatically create separate chunks for dynamic imports. No additional configuration needed:

```js
// vite.config.js - zero config for code splitting
// webpack.config.js - automatic with dynamic import()
```

### Chunk Naming with Magic Comments (Webpack)

```jsx
const AdminPanel = lazy(() =>
  import(/* webpackChunkName: "admin" */ './AdminPanel')
);
```

### Splitting Libraries

```jsx
// Split third-party libraries
const moment = await import('moment');
const _ = await import('lodash');
```

| Split Strategy | Granularity | Effort |
|---------------|-------------|--------|
| Route-based | Page chunks | Low |
| Component-based | Individual heavy components | Medium |
| Library-based | Third-party libs on demand | Medium |

### Preload for Anticipated Navigation

```jsx
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./Dashboard'));

// Preload when hovering over link
<link
  onMouseEnter={() => import('./Dashboard')}
  to="/dashboard"
>
  Dashboard
</link>
```

> **Key Point:** Use route-based code splitting by default. Check the Network tab to verify chunks are loading correctly. Avoid splitting components that are always needed on the first screen.

codeExample:
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';

const AdminRoutes = lazy(() => import('./admin/Routes'));
const UserRoutes = lazy(() => import('./user/Routes'));

function App() {
  const { role } = useAuth();

  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Loader />}>
      {role === 'admin' ? <AdminRoutes /> : <UserRoutes />}
    </Suspense>
  );
}
